My imagination has gotten better since I started but I am now aware of just how hard it is to imagine things instead of abstractions of said things.

That entire debacle came from people misunderstanding what your imagination is meant to look like. People gaslighted themselves into thinking that their imagination should be like autonomous VR/AR when you close your eyes, and that's how this retardation started. If you look at the aphantasia subreddit, a lot of people there do have an imagination, they just think they don't because of that misinterpretation or because they want to feel special by purposefully lying as it is often the case, like turning a slight discomfort at oddly shaped holes your brain's firmware is programmed to see as icky as an entire phobia to use as a special needs label.

>>69917229
Besides the whole misinterpretation of aphantasia, the thing I don't get the most is how I am capable of conceptualizing all the details of the apple at 1, but I feel like my imagination is a constant fluctuation between 1 and 3 if that makes sense. This entire topic is awful because that chart doesn't give all the crucial psychologic context of what's what and how to tell you're a 1 or a 3 or whatever, everyone interprets it willy-nilly and it's a complete mess. For example, I don't believe human imagination is capable of that VR/AR level of quality that 1 always seems to implies, it's always a dark blurry mess but you can make out those details, colors and shapes. It's a different signal to the same part of the brain that has to be treated differently.

Anonymous Sat 12 Oct 2024 20:01:26 No.69918178 Report
Quoted By: >>69918535 >>69918689 >>69920249
Speaking of birds:

>Review of Songbird by ReckfulAbandon

For a first AO3 story this is very good. Paced well and intriguing.

Many /hmofa/ stories have a human entering a new land of anthros, so it's refreshing to see the opposite happen and how a human village reacts to it.

The biggest highlight so far are the main characters.

Thomas comes off as simple without being bland, a man who is trying to get by but is struggling to know if he wants more in life. Enamored with the outside world but bolted down by his duty as a baker. He's also quick thinking, if a little impulsive. It's also nice to see a /hmofa/ protagonist who has frequent interactions with his family, and a healthy relationship with his sister.

A'Nikke initially came off as the less interesting character but that's changed with this chapter and her thinking of her feelings towards Thomas. It will be interesting to see how this story goes and the internal conflict that's brewing.

There are a few amateur writing mistakes. The biggest is paragraphing when it comes to dialogue and character actions. There's a few instances where I feel paragraphs need to be revised, split and sewn together. This is especially surrounding dialogue, which if blended into a paragraph wrong can rip a sentence to a halt.

The world-building is also a bit bland and uninteresting so far but as it's not the main focus and the story has a very small scope so far, this is a bit of a non issue. I assume this will be corrected in future chapters.

None of these floors make it unreadable however.

Overall, recommended for a short nice read.
Anonymous

2018? This place is not recognizable
